Easy way to remember
"How many degrees does each hand move in one minute?"
Minute hand:
360° / 60 = 6° per minute

Hour hand:
360° / (12 × 60) = 0.5° per minute

double minuteAngle;   // Position of minute hand
double hourAngle;     // Position of hour hand
double diff;          // Difference between the two angles

double minuteAngle = minutes * 6;
Angle of the minute hand from 12 o'clock.
Example: 30 minutes → 180°.

double hourAngle = (hour % 12) * 30 + minutes * 0.5;
Angle of the hour hand from 12 o'clock.
Example: 3:30 → 105°.

double diff = Math.abs(hourAngle - minuteAngle);
Distance between the two hands.

return Math.min(diff, 360 - diff);
Returns the smaller angle.

6    -> minute hand moves 6° per minute
30   -> hour hand moves 30° per hour
0.5  -> hour hand moves 0.5° per minute
360  -> full circle
12   -> clock hours
60   -> clock minutes






